{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492264"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:24:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1026"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1026"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.04,0.6,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90509"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1026"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74749"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"581"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31045"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90509"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents with a painless swelling on the left side of his face which has been present for four months. Recently it has been increasing in size. His medical history includes pulmonary tuberculosis, treated five years earlier. He is not on any medications. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history. He is a recent migrant from Malaysia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination is unremarkable, apart from the swelling (Image). The swelling is smooth-surfaced and well-defined.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tuberculous adenoma","Nasopharyngeal carcinoma","Pleomorphic adenoma of the parotid","Non-Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma","Lipoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe swelling is in the region of the parotid gland and until proven otherwise should be assumed to be a mixed parotid tumour (\u003Cstrong\u003Epleomorphicadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E). These adenomas are responsible for about 80% of parotid tumours. \u003Cstrong\u003ENasopharyngeal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E and tuberculosis must be considered in a patient who comes from a part of the world where these two conditions are relatively common. Whilst the swelling could be an enlarged preauricular lymph node, these enlarged nodes are usually more evident immediately anterior to the ear. Also, the fact that it has been present for four months with minimal size change, makes it unlikely to be metastatic disease, such as a nasopharyngeal carcinoma. This could be \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculous adenitis\u003C/strong\u003E, but more change would have been expected over this time period. It could be a \u003Cstrong\u003Elipoma\u003C/strong\u003E - but the face is an unusual site for these lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E would usually involve the cervical nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A swelling in the parotid region should be assumed to have originated from the parotid gland until proven otherwise."],"references":["Roland N, Bradley PJ. Neck swellings. BMJ 2014; 348:g1078."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74749"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1026"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20196"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media"